2902	[The preimage family of a quasi-coherence cover covers the source]
2903	  \label{lem:coversTop_preimage}
2904	  \lean{AlgebraicGeometry.Scheme.Modules.coversTop_preimage}
2905	  \uses{lem:isQuasicoherent_quasicoherentData_mathlib}
2906	  \textit{Preimages of a top cover under a morphism again cover the top.}
2907	  Let \(g : Y \to X\) be a morphism of schemes and \(q\) quasi-coherence data for a sheaf \(M\) on
2908	  \(X\), with cover \(\{q.X_i\}\) of \(X\) (\cref{lem:isQuasicoherent_quasicoherentData_mathlib}). Then
2909	  the preimage family \(\{\,W_i := g^{-1}(q.X_i)\,\}\) is a \(\mathrm{CoversTop}\) family on \(Y\).
2910	\end{lemma}
2911	\begin{proof}
2912	  \uses{lem:isQuasicoherent_quasicoherentData_mathlib}
2913	  The covering property \(q.\mathrm{coversTop}\) says \(\{q.X_i\}\) generates the maximal sieve on
2914	  \(\top_X\); pulling back along the continuous map underlying \(g\) commutes with the sieve operations
2915	  and sends \(\top_X\) to \(\top_Y\) (\(g^{-1}\top = \top\) and \(g^{-1}\) preserves suprema), so the
2916	  preimage family \(\{g^{-1}(q.X_i)\}\) generates the maximal sieve on \(\top_Y\), i.e.\ it covers the
2917	  top.
2918	\end{proof}
